Max Hardy is not a definitive source for what is and is not legal. :-)

According to Rick Beye, who *is* a definitive source (he's the ACBL's
Chief TD), the current ACBL position is that if a player considers a
hand to be &quot;strong&quot; (note that &quot;strong&quot; is not defined anywhere in the
laws or in ACBL regulations), then a 2C opening on that hand is not a
psych. I once held AKQJxxx Jxx - Jx. *I* didn't open it 2C (I wouldn't
have, but in fact my RHO opened 2D), but the opponent at the other
table did so (my teammate in first seat didn't like her diamond suit -
AQxxxx - so she passed). The bidding went 2C-2D-4S-AP, and our
teammates misdefended, not expecting this hand type for a 2C opener.
TD let the result stand. :-(

All that said, the original poster may not be in the ACBL - in which
case ACBL regulations are irrelevant.
</POST>
